WEBVTT

00:14.338 --> 00:21.148
Welcome to the Petty Profit Podcast, where we talk about news, politics, and culture from a Christian worldview.

00:21.168 --> 00:23.772
I am your host Joel Berry, and I am glad to be with you.

00:23.812 --> 00:25.194
Thank you for tuning in.

00:25.915 --> 00:32.003
A few months ago, I appeared as a guest on the StoryGeek's podcast, and we talked about the hero's journey.

00:32.564 --> 00:42.098
I will link to it in the show notes if you want to check that out, but I continued to listen to the podcast, and the other day I was listening to a discussion on Tolkien.

00:42.306 --> 00:43.528
and the Lord of the Rings.

00:43.548 --> 00:48.815
And they were talking about a term that I had never heard before, something called ucatastrophe.

00:49.216 --> 01:02.895
That's ucatastrophe spelled E-U-C-A-S-T-R-O-P-H-E. And it refers to that moment in all the best stories, the timeless stories, the fairy tales, the ones that have a happy ending.

01:03.135 --> 01:11.026
That moment where all hope seems lost, the hero's defeat seems imminent, and then suddenly

01:11.170 --> 01:12.713
Suddenly something happens.

01:13.656 --> 01:18.587
Something happens that allows the hero to triumph against all odds.

01:19.128 --> 01:21.433
And I was fascinated by that word and that concept.

01:21.493 --> 01:23.858
And so I decided to do a little digging into Tolkien.

01:23.878 --> 01:27.346
I read his essay called on fairy stories.

01:27.682 --> 01:28.563
And I loved it so much.

01:28.583 --> 01:31.267
I figured I would bring you some thoughts from it.

01:31.367 --> 01:33.730
So I hope you enjoy this week's episode.

01:33.770 --> 01:42.481
Before I jump into it here, I'll remind you that you can reach out to me at contact at thepetiprofit.com or you can go on to the website.

01:42.902 --> 01:46.246
It's thepetiprofit.com and you can click on the contact form.

01:46.667 --> 01:47.248
You can write me.

01:47.488 --> 01:49.010
You can ask questions.

01:49.090 --> 01:51.754
And if your question is good enough, we might answer it on the man hug.

01:51.975 --> 01:57.263
So we haven't done a question answer mailbag type episode on the podcast yet.

01:57.323 --> 02:01.349
So if there's something you'd like us to discuss, if you have a question, be sure to reach out.

02:01.850 --> 02:06.557
And as always, if you have a mind to do so, go to iTunes, give us five star review.

02:06.578 --> 02:14.049
That really helps us, helps us climb up the charts, beat that algorithm so that more listeners can find out about this podcast.

02:14.370 --> 02:17.074
It is all greatly appreciated and thank you for your support.

02:17.282 --> 02:20.746
But without further delay, let's jump into the episode.

02:21.407 --> 02:24.971
This week, we're talking about you catastrophe.

02:30.878 --> 02:40.730
Today, I would like to talk about mankind's greatest desire and most important need, a need that has been deeply felt by every human being throughout all of history.

02:40.830 --> 02:47.058
So naturally, I will be talking about escapist entertainment.

02:47.234 --> 03:00.709
on its face that sounds like a joke, but I think the connections between our greatest need and our most cherished myths, whether they be superhero flicks or space operas, whatever they are, I think those connections are deeper than they seem.

03:01.329 --> 03:03.131
I recently read J.R.R.

03:03.151 --> 03:13.422
Tolkien's essay on fairy stories, came away with so many thoughts, and I've struggled to really organize them and communicate them in a way that makes sense.

03:14.403 --> 03:16.946
And as you'll hopefully see a little bit when I

03:17.634 --> 03:18.735
delve further into this.

03:18.815 --> 03:28.507
That's what happens when you try to describe something divine and infinite, but hopefully at least some of this comes across to as a coherent thought.

03:29.048 --> 03:44.306
I loved Tolkien's essay on fairy stories and found it very encouraging because right now we live in insane times because everywhere we look in entertainment, social media, news in our cities,

03:44.770 --> 03:53.619
We are smacked in the head over and over again with depictions of mankind's cruelty, malice, malevolence, brokenness, and hatred.

03:54.400 --> 03:57.263
Everything seems to be crumbling all around us.

03:58.364 --> 04:01.046
Every one seems to be going insane.

04:01.867 --> 04:07.533
And the hope that any of this may get better seems to slip away a little more and more every day.

04:08.154 --> 04:12.498
So is this idea of escapist entertainment of Fool's errand?

04:13.570 --> 04:16.514
Well, it's definitely fallen out of fashion recently.

04:16.534 --> 04:34.556
Even our movies and TV shows that feature magic, spaceships, fantastical creatures, all seem obsessed with being steeped in grim, godless materialism with this idea of reminding the viewer about our present-day horrors and injustices.

04:35.357 --> 04:39.502
And it's possible true escapism never really was in fashion.

04:40.042 --> 04:43.026
I think at some level, our culture has always looked down

04:43.234 --> 04:45.057
on escapist entertainment.

04:45.678 --> 04:54.314
Our myths, our fairy tales, you know, the recent Marvel movies might be one example of this have always been seen as something less worthy.

04:54.995 --> 05:06.115
Escapism might be a nice emotional diversion, folks may say, but the most worthy stories in entertainment are those that address the problems in our world, in the here and now.

05:07.096 --> 05:08.018
Take this article

05:08.162 --> 05:16.591
I recently read, for example, and I'll link to it in the show notes, but the headline is, in the age of Trump, escapist entertainment has become an impossibility.

05:17.011 --> 05:32.287
And here the writer suggests that due to the gravely serious times we live in, quote, perhaps fiction, even the lighthearted television variety has a responsibility to keep us alert to our reality rather than inspire us to escape it.

05:33.328 --> 05:35.730
So is escapism foolish?

05:36.354 --> 05:38.877
are fairy stories as J.R.R.

05:38.918 --> 05:40.660
Tolkien described them foolish.

05:41.501 --> 05:46.468
To that question, Tolkien might smile and say, well, I don't know.

05:47.710 --> 05:52.216
Would you suggest to a prisoner or a slave that escapism is a fool's errand?

05:53.518 --> 05:56.862
You see, most of our culture today is in a prison.

05:57.423 --> 06:00.327
We are imprisoned by a philosophy called materialism.

06:00.848 --> 06:02.450
We have believed the lie

06:02.626 --> 06:10.276
that the physical universe is all there is, all there was, and all there ever will be, as Carl Sagan said.

06:10.316 --> 06:15.243
Only that which can be detected by the senses and through science should be considered real.

06:16.024 --> 06:19.549
So, we look for value within the four walls of the jail cell.

06:19.709 --> 06:21.932
We look for value and purpose and we don't find it.

06:22.333 --> 06:28.301
We look for morality, for goodness, for peace within those four walls and we don't find it.

06:28.942 --> 06:32.146
And our culture is angry and confused as a result.

06:32.962 --> 06:37.827
But imagine for a minute you have been imprisoned in this jail cell your whole life.

06:38.628 --> 06:42.772
You might have every reason to believe the four walls are all there is.

06:43.292 --> 06:49.378
But then imagine one day you see a sliver of bright light shine through the cracks in the door.

06:50.099 --> 06:54.323
Or maybe you hear birds chirping outside or the sound of children laughing.

06:54.984 --> 06:57.506
You might start to wonder about the world outside.

06:57.987 --> 07:01.330
Maybe you'd even start to long for it to know more about it.

07:02.050 --> 07:04.995
or perhaps even escape to it.

07:05.936 --> 07:20.821
And that's my problem with some of the big pieces of entertainment that have captured the public imagination in recent years, and I'll cite two examples, the first one being Game of Thrones and the second one being The Last of Us, which was a video game, if you're not into video games.

07:21.382 --> 07:21.662
Sorry.

07:23.265 --> 07:26.610
But Game of Thrones really captured the imagination of our culture.

07:27.330 --> 07:34.442
I think part of the reason it was so effective is that it was brutally honest about the darkness and unfairness of the physical world.

07:35.283 --> 07:36.525
It was bleak.

07:36.545 --> 07:38.068
It was horrifically bleak.

07:38.809 --> 07:39.951
And it was that way on purpose.

07:40.812 --> 07:46.001
George RR Martin, the writer of the books that inspired the show, is a self-proclaimed atheist.

07:46.662 --> 07:54.194
And he set out to write, in his words, an answer to Tolkien, an anti- Tolkien fantasy tale, a more realistic one.

07:54.498 --> 08:00.886
One where evil often wins and heroic character arcs get inexplicably cut short by rape or murder.

08:01.787 --> 08:07.174
In this universe, power is an end unto itself, and religion is just another political tool.

08:07.714 --> 08:11.319
It's life in the state of nature, nasty, brutish, and short.

08:12.000 --> 08:15.203
In our Martin's universe, human beings are just another animal.

08:15.724 --> 08:23.794
Just like worms, wolves, and fish, they're in an endless cycle of living, eating, mating, fighting, and dying that continues forever.

08:24.066 --> 08:25.067
In the words of R.R.

08:25.107 --> 08:32.476
Martin, in an interview with Entertainment Weekly, he said, if there's a benevolent loving God, why is the world full of rape and torture?

08:33.397 --> 08:34.578
Why do we even have pain?

08:35.279 --> 08:44.689
And in his honest, unflinching look at the reality within the four walls of our physical existence, Martin created a very engaging work of fiction.

08:45.210 --> 08:49.495
But many, who watched the show, unsurprisingly walked away feeling hopeless.

08:50.656 --> 08:52.178
The Last of Us, part two,

08:52.706 --> 09:05.360
video game, and a more recent example, might appear to be escapist since it involves apocalyptic cities and zombies, but like Game of Thrones, it approaches reality with the bleak outlook of materialism.

09:05.820 --> 09:19.135
It goes out of its way to kill beloved characters with senseless cruelty, to cut short character arcs before they can be complete, and remind you time and time again that human beings are awful, horrible creatures who do awful, horrible things.

09:19.635 --> 09:22.258
It all unfolds just as it might in real life.

09:22.626 --> 09:24.949
And the intention of the storytellers is clear here.

09:25.509 --> 09:32.097
The message is this, that the universe is all there is, all there was, and all there ever will be.

09:33.078 --> 09:39.665
There is no design, no grand storyteller, no creator, or just creatures fighting it out in a Petri dish.

09:39.965 --> 09:46.653
This isn't good or evil, it's one man's good versus another man's good, and it all results in senseless death either way.

09:47.194 --> 09:51.218
And again, people who play the game walked away feeling hopeless.

09:51.810 --> 09:59.180
Now, in both of these cases, people blame poor writing for how unsatisfying these stories were, but I think that's only half the problem.

10:00.041 --> 10:11.718
These stories don't resonate, because while they tell the story of the physical world very effectively, they are only telling half the story, because the physical world isn't all there is.

10:13.600 --> 10:14.902
Now enter J.R.R.

10:14.982 --> 10:20.690
Tolkien, and the fairy tale, and what Tolkien called the euchatastrophe,

10:20.898 --> 10:23.082
which means good catastrophe.

10:23.582 --> 10:40.731
In a euchatastrophe, the storyteller, after establishing the dismal hopelessness of physical reality, then consoles us with a glimpse of a higher reality, where right and wrong, good and evil, justice and mercy are all as real as the flesh on our bones.

10:41.392 --> 10:47.762
In these stories, just when all hope seems lost, and the hero's defeat seems sure,

10:48.194 --> 10:56.087
When the pain and sorrow of existence are portrayed with painful honesty, there is a sudden straightening of the universe towards ultimate justice.

10:56.748 --> 11:03.560
This is the point in the story, the book or the movie, where the hero triumphs over evil against all odds.

11:04.341 --> 11:07.747
And for the euchatastrophe to work, it has to make logical sense in the story.

11:07.827 --> 11:09.269
It can't be a cheap trick.

11:09.670 --> 11:14.578
It must have, as Tolkien said, the inner consistency of reality.

11:14.882 --> 11:21.693
And when it's properly executed, it results in an almost spiritual experience of joy and relief.

11:22.014 --> 11:25.960
You'll feel goosebumps, you'll shed tears, you'll clap, and you'll cheer.

11:26.601 --> 11:32.891
Just listen to some of these audience reactions during the moment of euchatastrophe in the Avengers.

11:33.272 --> 11:41.906
When all hope seems lost, defeat is inevitable, and then suddenly the Avengers are resurrected and unite to fight the villain Thanos.

12:05.442 --> 12:15.251
There was no denying the effectiveness of that scene, you know, with the score in that moment of incredible triumph in the face of tremendous odds.

12:15.812 --> 12:23.919
You can go on YouTube and you can find dozens of these just rapturous theater reactions to this moment of euchatastrophe in the movie, The Avengers.

12:24.079 --> 12:35.410
But for me, nothing tops the battle of Helms Deep in Lord of the Rings, The Two Towers, the second book in the series, the second movie in that trilogy.

12:35.874 --> 12:42.945
And I had the pleasure of experiencing this moment for the first time having never read the books, so I didn't know how it was going to end.

12:43.405 --> 12:46.450
Here we see the heroes facing certain defeat.

12:46.991 --> 12:55.864
Their boxed in at Helms Deep, Saron's forces have breached the walls of the city and will soon reach the inner caverns where the women and children are hiding.

12:57.287 --> 13:02.194
We see eight-year-old boys being fitted with helmets and swords too large for them.

13:02.594 --> 13:06.338
their lips trembling as they prepare to fight and die to the last.

13:06.898 --> 13:08.880
There is nothing that can stop the slaughter.

13:09.260 --> 13:10.942
But then the sun rises.

13:11.623 --> 13:17.709
We look to the east and we see Gandalf on a hill overlooking the battle with a cavalry at his back.

13:18.149 --> 13:22.093
He charges Sauron's army and we are treated to this moment.

13:22.573 --> 13:31.442
And try and notice the one dissonant cord as the charging armies collide as good meets evil, light meets dark, hope meets despair.

13:59.842 --> 14:08.054
These are moments of true escapism, the very best kind, when people are given a glimpse of the light outside our dreary four walls.

14:09.176 --> 14:13.602
A glimpse of ultimate reality, ultimate justice, ultimate truth.

14:14.183 --> 14:20.913
It's when all the hopes and desires of the audience are met in one decisive moment.

14:20.933 --> 14:25.981
Tolkien described the euchatastrophe this way in his essay on fairy stories.

14:26.021 --> 14:29.426
He said, It is a sudden and miraculous grace

14:29.602 --> 14:31.404
never to be counted on to recur.

14:31.785 --> 14:34.509
It does not deny the existence of sorrow and failure.

14:34.889 --> 14:38.294
The possibility of these is necessary to the joy of deliverance.

14:38.314 --> 14:45.664
Instead, it denies, in the face of much evidence, if you will, the idea of universal final defeat.

14:46.184 --> 14:48.748
It is Evangelium, the good news.

14:49.889 --> 14:56.338
Giving a fleeting glimpse of joy, joy beyond the walls of this world, every bit as poignant as grief.

14:56.642 --> 15:11.609
joy which produces tears because it is qualitatively so like sorrow, because it comes from those places where joy and sorrow are at one, reconciled, as selfishness and altruism are lost in love.

15:12.571 --> 15:16.197
Now there's no denying the power of such a moment in storytelling.

15:16.999 --> 15:21.106
I think it's because the glory outside these dreary four walls is real.

15:21.602 --> 15:28.530
I could try against everything I observe in reality to deny it or suppress it, but there's no denying we all have a longing within us.

15:29.471 --> 15:33.275
Euchatastrophe is not just a consolation for the sorrow of the world.

15:34.136 --> 15:35.898
It is the satisfaction of a longing.

15:36.519 --> 15:49.874
And if you found yourself unsatisfied by the stories of Game of Thrones, or The Last of Us, or others, I would urge you to pay attention to where that dissatisfaction is coming from, and reflect on what you might be longing for.

15:50.498 --> 15:54.423
And here is where we get one step closer to the story of Christianity.

15:55.264 --> 15:55.625
C.S.

15:55.645 --> 16:03.435
Lewis, in his fantasy world of Narnia, had what he called the Deep Magic, something that we Christians call the Law of Sin and Death.

16:04.877 --> 16:06.839
We all know about the Deep Magic.

16:06.979 --> 16:08.421
We experience it every day.

16:08.822 --> 16:15.210
But if you read Lewis' Narnia books, you'll know there is also something called the Deeper Magic from before the dawn of time.

16:15.610 --> 16:18.354
We might call that the Law of the Spirit of Life,

16:18.466 --> 16:20.648
made possible by the sacrifice of Jesus.

16:21.249 --> 16:29.759
All the sorrow, heartbreak, and condemnation of our sin met the infinite love of God and it happened the moment the word became flesh.

16:30.320 --> 16:37.207
The Old Testament with its horrific war, bloodshed, and death showed us the catastrophe, the law of sin and death.

16:37.588 --> 16:40.471
The birth of Christ was mankind's euchatastrophe.

16:41.072 --> 16:46.578
The crucifixion with its horrific murder of innocent Jesus showed us the catastrophe

16:46.946 --> 16:51.731
the law of sin and death, but the resurrection was our euchatastrophe.

16:52.372 --> 16:55.976
All of history, past and present, points to this event.

16:56.557 --> 17:02.524
All of our storytelling looks back to it and looks forward to the joy of eternity and ultimate justice.

17:02.544 --> 17:09.472
Today, we are limited to a fleeting glimpse, array of sunlight, or the sound of laughter outside the jail cell.

17:10.893 --> 17:15.058
As the scriptures say, we see through a glass darkly, but someday,

17:15.234 --> 17:29.827
will be face to face with ultimate truth, ultimate justice, and ultimate love and grace in the stories that tell the whole truth, both the truth of our present reality and the truth of the higher reality, the deeper magic.

17:31.110 --> 17:33.074
Those are the stories that stick with you.

